description: Hot dog vendors and coffee carts turn to a black market operating in the open to buy permits and licenses, and even contest tickets with the city | Crain's New York Business
extended: When Sharif leaves his home in Flushing, Queens, it’s too early to say goodbye to his wife and three kids. Long before sunrise, he drives 15 minutes to a cold, brightly lit garage in Long Island City that smells of spent fuel, cleaning fluid and food that’s about to turn.
